TITLE: Using @psalm-taint-unescape for HTML decoding in PHP
DESCRIPTION: This example demonstrates how to properly annotate a function that decodes HTML entities back to their original form using the @psalm-taint-unescape annotation. The function converts encoded characters like &lt; back to <, which makes previously safe content potentially dangerous again.
SOURCE: https://github.com/catchpoint/webpagetest/blob/master/vendor/vimeo/psalm/docs/security_analysis/avoiding_false_negatives.md#2025-04-21_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: php
CODE:
```
<?php

/**
 * @psalm-taint-unescape html
 */
function decode(string $str): string
{
    return str_replace(
        ['&lt;', '&gt;', '&quot;', '&apos;'],
        ['<', '>', '"', '"'],
        $str
    );
}

$safe = htmlspecialchars($_GET['text']);
echo decode($safe);
```

